As I said, that demo has "sorter-false" set... it should be "sorter-text".

Or, you can add a definition to the [`headers` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#headers):

```js
jQuery("#groupe").tablesorter({
	sortList: [[0,0]],
	headers: {
		1: { sorter: 'text' }
	}
});
```

There are other ways to set a column parser - see [this demo](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-parsers-class-name.html) for more information. I didn't include that extra information here to avoid confusion.

The reason the parser is being set to image, is because the automatic parser detector is seeing an image in the first cell of that column. If you don't want the alt information from the image used by the sorter, you'll need to set a different sorter.

Hi Fábio!

You can bind to the "pagerChange" event and scroll the window to the top ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/1a5yu8yq/99/)):

In that demo, shrink the result window down and set the page size to 30 - it may not do this if you've been to jsFiddle before since the page size is being saved to local storage. Then scroll to the bottom and change pages.. the `.scrollTop` function will move you to the top of the page

```js
$(function () {
	$('table').on('pagerChange', function(){
  	$(window).scrollTop(0);
  }).tablesorter({
		theme: 'blue',
	}).tablesorterPager({
		container: $('.pager'),
    size: 30
	});
});
```

